<DOC><DOCNO> AP880613-0225 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 0950EDT</FILEID><FIRST>a a BC-History Adv23   06-13 0487</FIRST><SECOND>BC-History, Adv23,0507</SECOND><NOTE>$Adv23</NOTE><NOTE>For Release Thursday, June 23</NOTE><HEAD>Today in History</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>      Today is Thursday, June 23, the 175th day of 1988. There are 191days left in the year.   Today's Highlight in History:   On June 23, 1947, the Senate joined the House of Representativesin overriding President Harry S. Truman's veto of the Taft-HartleyAct. The new law banned the closed shop, provided for a ``coolingoff'' period before strikes, required union finances to be madepublic and prohibited unions from making donations to politicalcampaigns.   On this date:   In 1683, William Penn signed a friendship treaty with the LenniLenape Indians near present-day Philadelphia.   In 1868, Christopher Latham Sholes received a patent for aninvention he called a ``Type-Writer.''   In 1931, aviators Wiley Post and Harold Catty took off from NewYork for a flight around the world.   In 1938, the Civil Aeronautics Authority was established.   In 1956, Gamal Abdel Nasser was elected president of Egypt.   In 1967, the U.S. Senate voted to censure Democrat Thomas J.Dodd of Connecticut for using campaign money for personal uses.   In 1967, President Lyndon B. Johnson and Soviet Premier AlexeiKosygin held the first of two meetings in Glassboro, N.J.   In 1969, Warren E. Burger was sworn in as chief justice of theUnited States by the man he was succeeding, Earl Warren.   In 1972, President Richard M. Nixon and White House chief ofstaff H.R. Haldeman agreed to use the CIA to obstruct the FBI'sWatergate investigation. (The revelation of the White Houserecording of this conversation resulted in Nixon's resignation inAugust 1974.)   In 1985, all 329 people aboard an Air-India Boeing 747 werekilled when the plane crashed into the Atlantic Ocean near Ireland.   Ten years ago: The United States recalled George W. Landau, theU.S. ambassador to Chile, charging the Chilean government had notcooperated enough in the investigation of the 1976 murders offormer Chilean diplomat Orlando Letelier and an associate inWashington.   Five years ago: In a ruling that effectively shifted the balanceof powers in the federal government, the U.S. Supreme Court struckdown, 7-2, the so-called ``legislative veto,'' which Congress hadused to curtail the powers of the executive branch.   One year ago: The Iran-Contra hearings resumed after a two-weekbreak. Former CIA employee Glenn A. Robinette testified he hadinstalled a $14,000 security system at the home of Lt. Col. OliverNorth, then helped make it appear that North had paid for the work.   Today's Birthdays: Advertising executive David Ogilvy is 77.Former Secretary of State William P. Rogers is 75. Actress IreneWorth is 72. Singer June Carter Cash is 59. Olympic hall-of-famerWilma Rudolph is 48. Musical conductor James Levine is 45. ActorTed Shackelford is 42.   Thought for Today: ``To forgive and forget means to throwvaluable experience out the window.'' _ Arthur Schopenhauer, Germanphilosopher (1788-1860).</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv</NOTE></DOC>